                        Aaron is a presbyter from <span class="tei-placeName"><a href="http://syriaca.org/place/576">Armenia</a></span> who is commemorated in the Lives of the Eastern
                        Saints by <span class="tei-persName"><a href="http://syriaca.org/person/74">John of
                            Ephesus</a></span>.</span><span class="tei-footnote-refs" dir="ltr" lang="en" xml:lang="en"><span class="tei-footnote-ref"><a href="#bib1533-1">1</a></span> </span></div><div style="margin:0 1em 1em; color: #999999;"><small><p><span class="srp-label"><strong>Syriaca.org URI</strong></span>: <span id="syriaca-id"><a href="http://syriaca.org/person/1533">http://syriaca.org/person/1533</a></span></p></small></div></div><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns" class="row"><div class="col-md-8"><div class="sources"><h3>Personal Information</h3><h4>Name variant(s): </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-listPerson">
                    <span class="tei-person">
                        <span class="tei-persName"> Aaron </span>
                    </span>
                </span> <a href="/829-1" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent"><span class="tei-listPerson">
                    <span class="tei-personGrp">
                        <span class="tei-persName"> Aaron </span>
                    </span>
                </span> <a href="/830-10" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Birth: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">Birth place: </span><span class="tei-persName">Aaron</span>
                                was born in the country of <span class="tei-placeName">Armenia</span>.
                             <a href="/829-5" class="factoid-more"> See factoid page <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Death: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">Death date: </span>569 <a href="/830-22" class="factoid-more"> See factoid page <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">Death date: </span> 22 October 560 A.D.  22 Teshri I 872 A. G. <a href="/829-6" class="factoid-more"> See factoid page <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Sex: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Aaron</span> was male.  <a href="/830-11" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Place of residence: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Aaron</span>
                                dwelled with <span class="tei-persName">John of
                                    Ephesus</span> for a period of thirty years in the
                                    <span class="tei-placeName">royal
                                    city</span>.  <a href="/829-16" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Sanctity: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Aaron</span>
                                was a saint.
                             <a href="/829-15" class="factoid-more"> See factoid page <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Occupation(s): </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Aaron</span>
                                was a priest.  <a href="/829-10" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Aaron</span>
                                was a qašišā.  <a href="/830-12" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Aaron</span>
                                was a monk.  <a href="/830-13" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Aaron</span>
                                was a Presbyter.  <a href="/829-2" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Aaron</span>
                                was a monk.  <a href="/829-9" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Physical Trait: </h4><p class="indent">
                
                <span class="tei-listPerson">
                    <span class="tei-person">
                        <span class="tei-persName"/>
                        <span class="tei-persName">Aaron</span> had sore diseases and lost his loin to
                                gangrene. 
                    </span>
                </span>
                
                
             <a href="/829-11" class="factoid-more"> See factoid page <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p></div><div class="sources"><h3>Relationships</h3><p class="indent">
                            John of Ephesus 
                            commemorated
                            Aaron.
                         <a href="/829-14" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent">Leontius, Aaron and Qashish were monks at the same monastery. <a href="/830-15" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent">John of Ephesus, Leontius and Aaron were acquainted. <a href="/830-18" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent">Leontius and Aaron had a friendship. <a href="/830-21" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p></div><div class="sources"><h3>Events</h3><p class="indent">Aaron had a surgery,
                            placing a tube of lead to allow him to urinate and treated with
                            medication. Then he was healed. Allowing him to live for another 18
                            years.  <a href="/829-12" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">
                            Aaron died from old age on
                            
                                 22 October 560
                                    A.D. 
                                 22 Teshri I 872 A. G.
                                
                            
                            and he was laid in the sepulchre that
                            was built by the blessed Mare.
                         <a href="/829-13" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">Abraham
                            and Zwtʾ and Daniel and Aaron and Leontius missionize
                            in the district of Asia.  <a href="/831-14" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">Aaron passed the
                            days of his life in a monastic convent in retreat and religion, from the
                            early age of his youth.  <a href="/829-7" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">Aaron so, when he
                            had attained to the order of the priesthood.  <a href="/829-8" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">Leontius was
                            buried alongside of the
                                Blessed Aaron at the Monastery of Yoḥannan
                                Urṭaya <a href="/830-9" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/></div><div class="citation"><h3>How to cite:</h3><span class="element">
